\par\par \b \uc2  Local car industry to face greater challenge in 1998. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Devi M. Asmarani \par \uc2 1,407 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 December 1997\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  10 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1997 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The Indonesian car industry, one of the worst hit sectors during this year's financial upheaval, will probably have to travel an even rockier road next year, with the worst jolts expected to come from gloomy sales and inflated import costs. \par \par \uc2  Automotive analysts, car producers and the Association of Indonesian Automotive Industries (Gaikindo) agree that the sector is unlikely to repeat the impressive growth it enjoyed last year and during the first half of this year. \par \par \uc2  They say people's weakening purchasing power will probably mean car sales will drop as much as 50 percent next year, while the rising costs of imported parts will force local car companies to tighten their \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  belts. \par \par \uc2  Gaikindo predicts that between 180,000 cars and 240,000 cars will be sold next year. It recorded 354,064 car sales from January to October this year. \par \par \uc2  "Realistically, the number of cars sold will be about 200,000 next year," Gaikindo secretary-general F. Soeseno told The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2  Soeseno said the currency crisis, which has caused the rupiah's value to drop almost 60 percent since July, had increased the prices of imported goods, making cars twice as expensive as they were. \par \par \uc2  At the same time the tight monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  imposed by the government to cope with the crisis has raised loan \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  so that buying or leasing a car is also very expensive. \par \par \uc2  The association's data shows that until last August car sales were on an upward trend with 4 percent to 5 percent growth monthly. \par \par \uc2  In September, the number began to slide 18 percent to 35,238 cars, and 12 percent to 30,788 cars in October. \par \par \uc2  Car analyst Suhari estimated car sales slumped 40 percent to 18,183 cars in November, while this month car sales might not exceed 10,000. \par \par \uc2  Soeseno said the sales decline would not stop car producers from increasing their prices. \par \par \uc2  He said car companies would have to adjust to inflation by raising prices 10 percent a month for at least the first half of next year. \par \par \uc2  This would be followed by a slowdown in their business expansion, he said. \par \par \uc2  Production cut \par \par \uc2  Expansion projects will be shelved and production capacities will be reduced resulting in mass layoffs in the car industry. \par \par \uc2  Soeseno said some companies had already begun reducing production by cutting their workers' shifts. \par \par \uc2  Gaikindo data shows that in the last two months, car assembling production dropped 43 percent to 19,246 cars in November from 34,110 cars in October. \par \par \uc2  November production was 41.5 percent lower than the same period last year, in which 32,946 cars were produced. \par \par \uc2  Suhari predicted that monthly car sales next year would not exceed 20,000 cars. \par \par \uc2  Should the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  recover by mid 1998, sales might pick up to about 25,000 cars a month until the end of the year, he said. \par \par \uc2  The sales of middle market cars such Toyota Kijang would drop sharply by about 50 percent, as buyers of this type of car usually lease or get loans to buy the cars. \par \par \uc2  Interest rate rises would stop them from getting loans, he said. \par \par \uc2  Truck sales would also drop as \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity would not remain as robust as in other years, and many companies would have to postpone expansion projects, he said. \par \par \uc2  The drop in sedan sales would be between 25 percent and 30 percent, while that of commercial cars would be about 45 percent, he said. \par \par \uc2  "The only category that will most likely suffer the lowest drop next year will be luxury sedans, because the purchasing power of these buyers will remain very strong," he told the Post. \par \par \uc2  But the sales volume of these cars would be so insignificant that it would have little impact on the whole automotive industry, he said. \par \par \uc2  PT Bimantara Citra Mobil Nasional, maker of Cakra and Nenggala sedans, has had to revise their revenue projection for next year. \par \par \uc2  Bimantara's president Jongkie D. Sugiarto said the company expected a 40 percent drop in its sales next year from an estimated 5,000 cars sold this year. \par \par \uc2  On a more positive note, the survival skills of local car companies next year will determine their success in the long run, Suhari said. \par \par \uc2  "Next year is the year of determining whether the Indonesian car industry will rise or fall, which companies will survive and which will collapse." \par \par \uc2  By 2000, when the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentives for local car production are lifted and import \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  are lowered, local car companies would have to be extra competitive, he said. \par \par \uc2  "Those which survive next year, will probably be able to compete in the liberalized market." \par \par \uc2  Indonesia has agreed to reduce import duty, now as high as 175 percent, on built-up cars by 2000 in return for the bail-out program arranged by the International Monetary Fund to cope with the Indonesian monetary crisis. \par \par \uc2  Details of the government's measure are expected to be announced during the new ministerial cabinet meeting next April, after the Presidential election. \par \par \uc2  Bimantara, which had formed a joint venture with South Korea's Hyundai Motor Co to produce cars with a more than 60 percent local content, were forced to shelve their US$400 million project early this week because of financial difficulties and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  over the new car \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  According to the existing \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , assemblers of passenger cars are given \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentives - cuts in the import duty and value added \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  - to deepen their manufacturing operations. \par \par \uc2  Cars with a local content of less than 20 percent are, for example, subject to an import duty of 65 percent for their imported materials and value added \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  of 35 percent. Those with local content of above 60 percent are exempted from the import \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  but are still subject to a 20 percent value added \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Jongkie said if the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentives were eliminated and import duty was drastically cut in 2000, there would be no sense in continuing the project to build a plant, which was expected to begin producing in mid 1999. \par \par \uc2  "Importing cars would be a better choice than making them here then," he said. \par \par \uc2  If the new measures exclude \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  exemptions on cars with over 60 percent local content, it is expected to affect the Timor car project as well. \par \par \uc2  Timor Putra, controlled by President Soeharto's youngest son Hutomo Mandala Putra, was granted import duty and luxury \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  exemptions to be the sole producer of a so-called national car, driving its cost 60 percent below that of other cars in Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  The company is cooperating with South Korea's Kia Motors Corp to produce the car. Until its ongoing construction of production facilities are completed mid next year, Timor is allowed to import fully assembled cars from South Korea. \par \par \uc2  Suhari said the entrance of the much disputed Timor cars into the domestic market was one of the most important events in the local car industry this year. \par \par \uc2  "Although Timor has not been as successful as it had anticipated, it grabbed about 25 percent of the market this year," he said. \par \par \uc2  Between January and November this year, Timor sold about 18,193 cars, or 40.8 percent of the market share. It was followed by Suzuki Baleno which sold 10,630 cars, and Toyota Corolla 4,702 cars. \par \par \uc2  Suhari said Timor, however, would not be as strong as other more established car companies with strong affiliations with their principals. \par \par \uc2  These companies, the primary group, would be the most likely to survive next year's hardships as their principals would help them through the crisis, he said. \par \par \uc2  The principals of these companies, including Toyota, Mitsubishi, Suzuki, Isuzu, Daihatsu, and Mercedes Benz trucks, could not pull out from their businesses here without inflicting a big financial impact on themselves, he said. \par \par \uc2  "For example, Toyota made so much profit from the sales of Kijang here, so that it would do anything to boost their partnership with Astra," he said, adding that the same would happen with Daihatsu and Suzuki-made commercial cars. \par \par \uc2  Cars belonging to the second group, including the Timor cars, Bimantara and Opel cars, could survive or even move up a rank if they could enlarge their market shares. \par \par \uc2  But otherwise, these cars could end up being imported only, like cars in the third group, like Fords, Mazdas, Daewo-made cars, he said. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1997 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011001dtct003mu\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picsca