\par\par \b \uc2  Two million lose their jobs during crisis - ABRI. \b0\par\par\uc2 471 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 January 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  2 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The Indonesian Armed Forces (ABRI) estimated yesterday that as many as two million people have lost their jobs since the monetary crisis began last July. \par \par \uc2  Armed Forces spokesman Brig. Gen. A. Wahab Mokodongan said such a crisis could destabilize the country, especially when people were easily provoked by speculation and rumors. \par \par \uc2  "However, ABRI members are ready to crack down on any security-disturbing activities," Wahab told journalists yesterday. \par \par \uc2  He said ABRI would always be prepared to face the worst situation, particularly if it could disturb national stability. \par \par \uc2  In the middle of the worst ever monetary crisis, the country is now preparing for the five-yearly general meeting of the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) next March, which will elect a president and a vice president and also endorse the 1998/2003 State \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Guidelines. \par \par \uc2  When asked about the accuracy of his estimations, Wahab said it was made under the best calculations possible from various reports. \par \par \uc2  "It was based on reports that many companies and industries had recently laid off their workers," he said. \par \par \uc2  Estimations on the number of people laid off vary, but most people say the figures are well above one million. According to the government, the one million figure was too high. \par \par \uc2  Last Tuesday, the Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry (Kadin) estimated that at least one million workers had lost their jobs. \par \par \uc2  The head of the Jakarta Chamber of Commerce and Industry, Yulia Hasan, said last week that 2.4 million workers had lost their jobs in Jakarta and the surrounding towns. \par \par \uc2  But Minister of Manpower Abdul Latief brushed aside these figures, saying the number was much lower. He promised to intensify training programs to help Indonesian workers fill many positions occupied by foreigners. \par \par \uc2  Wahab urged Indonesian companies to try not to dismiss their employees and workers despite the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. \par \par \uc2  "They can still employ their workers on a shift basis," he said. "Each shift works daily according to schedule by turns." \par \par \uc2  Analysts have warned that unemployment would rise through the year as companies struggle with big debts in foreign currencies, despite a multibillion dollar \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  rescue package put together by the International Monetary Fund (IMF). \par \par \uc2  President Soeharto is scheduled to announce the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  strategy, when he delivers the 1998 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  before the 500-member \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  (DPR) Tuesday evening. \par \par \uc2  One contributing factor to the rupiah's depreciation has been the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  surrounding Soeharto's health. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah fell dramatically against the U.S. dollar last month after doctors ordered the President to rest following a long overseas trip. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah fell further to its lowest ever point after rumors that the President had died and there would be a coup attempt. None of the rumors were true. (imn) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du130070m\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
