\par\par \b \uc2  Capital market dismal for new listings. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Aloysius Unditu \par \uc2 914 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 January 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  12 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Nineteen ninety-seven has gone and 1998 has arrived. But a different year does not necessarily mean a positive change in the country's capital market. \par \par \uc2  Nineteen ninety-eight does not yet offer good prospects for new listings, securities analysts predict. \par \par \uc2  "I think there will only be a few companies which will launch their initial \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  offerings (IPO) this year," a senior analyst at Bahana Securities told The Jakarta Post yesterday. \par \par \uc2  According to data provided by the Jakarta Stock Exchange (JSX), the number of companies which listed their shares on the JSX last year was 30, raising Rp 3.5 trillion (US$683 million) in funds from the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The number of the new listings was much higher than the initial target. \par \par \uc2  Analysts earlier predicted the number of IPOs would decline in 1997 due to unfavorable political climate during the general election last May. \par \par \uc2  However, the prediction turned out to be wrong. The number of the new listings in 1997 was the highest in the last three years. \par \par \uc2  In 1996, there were only 16 new listings, raising about Rp 2.4 trillion in fresh funds, while in 1995 the number of companies which floated their shares on the JSX was 22, raising Rp 6 trillion in funds. \par \par \uc2  The analyst from Bahana said the shares of resource-based companies would be more attractive than those offered by other firms during the monetary crisis. \par \par \uc2  "But there are only a few companies in this category," he said. \par \par \uc2  Property and banking sectors, believed to be the hardest hit by the currency crisis, would still face difficulty in entering the equity market. \par \par \uc2  "Even if property and banking companies force themselves to proceed with their IPO plans, there will be no securities companies that have the courage to underwrite their \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  offerings," the analyst said. \par \par \uc2  Head of research at Socgen Crosby Securities Indonesia Goei Siauw Hong shared the analyst's view. \par \par \uc2  Hong said even if some companies proceeded with their IPO plans, they would fail because many investors would stay away from the market. \par \par \uc2  Stock analysts said stock prices on the JSX, which had seen strong performance in the first half of 1997 with the JSX composite index breaking its highest record of 740.83 on July 7, were expected to continue declining, at least up until the second half this year. \par \par \uc2  Some stock analysts with a more pessimistic view expected the downward trend to continue until the end of the first three quarters this year. \par \par \uc2  Most foreign investors, which controlled more than 65 percent of transactions on the JSX before the monetary crisis hit the country last July, were unlikely to return to the market if \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  remained, they said. \par \par \uc2  "We expect the market to decline further in the first nine months this year due to high-profile bankruptcies and earnings disappointments by most companies," Hong told The Post yesterday. \par \par \uc2  The monetary crisis, which has seen the rupiah lose 65 percent of its value since July last year, has not shown any signs of recovery. \par \par \uc2  Some analysts said instability in the currency exchange rates would push foreigners away from the market due to \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  of a return on their investment in U.S. dollars. \par \par \uc2  They said the instability of the rupiah would also put pressure on \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which would be harmful to the market. \par \par \uc2  Faced with such bearish sentiment, most stock analysts predicted there would be a decline in IPOs this year. \par \par \uc2  According to data compiled by The Post, some companies which will go ahead with their IPOs this year include PT Danayasa Arthatama, PT Elnusa, PT Krakatau Steel, PT Sempati Air, PT Timor Distributor, PT Bintuni Minaraya, PT Pelabuhan Indonesia, PT Bank Baja, PT Impact Pratama and PT Margamasa Griya Realty. \par \par \uc2  PT Danayasa Arthatama is expected to raise about $225 million from its IPO this year. PT Elnusa, a subsidiary of state-owned oil company PT Pertamina, is expected to offer about 200 million shares to the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  and raise Rp 300 billion. \par \par \uc2  PT Elnusa, a joint venture between Pertamina and PT Tridaya Esta, a minority shareholder in the company currently owned by businessmen Bambang Trihatmodjo, the second son of President Soeharto, and Indra Bambang Utoyo, is a subsidiary of Pertamina dealing with telecommunications-related services. \par \par \uc2  The company has five main business divisions: oil and gas exploration and production, information and telecommunications, oil refinery, retail oil production, and infrastructure development. \par \par \uc2  PT Krakatau Steel, another strategic state enterprise, is expected to offer between 30 percent to 40 percent of its total enlarged capital to the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  to raise about $600 million. \par \par \uc2  PT Sempati Air is expected to raise Rp 200 billion by offering 15 percent to 20 percent of its total enlarged capital. \par \par \uc2  PT Bintuni Minaraya is to raise about Rp 400 billion, PT Pelabuhan Indonesia is to raise Rp 2 trillion, Bank Baja is to raise Rp 62.5 billion and Impact Pratama is to raise Rp 80 billion. \par \par \uc2  Some analysts said only companies with strong fundamentals and revenue generated in dollars had managed to sail clear of the stormy waters last year. \par \par \uc2  State-owned gold and nickel producer PT Aneka Tambang and plantation firm PT Astra Agro Lestari of the Astra International Group were among companies which were successful in their \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  offerings last year. \par \par \uc2  "If that is an indication of success, other companies which are not included in this category will face failure," an analyst said. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du1800789\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Non-oil/gas projected revenue seen as unrealistic. \b0\par\par\uc2 229 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 January 1998\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  The government's 1998/99 budgetary revenue target of non-oil/gas items of Rp 80.4 trillion - up 9.9% over the previous \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  - would be difficult to achieve because that particular sector is in the midst of a slump that negatively effects exports while the country's products have yet to raise its competitiveness in the international market, economist Soeharsono Sagir told Bisnis in comments over the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The new \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  forecasts an income of Rp 27.3 trillion from oil/gas and Rp 80.4 trillion from non-oil/gas items. \par \par \uc2  Sagir noted that the rupiah deprecation has made imported raw materials more expensive, causing a slump in domestic production. \par \par \uc2  But, he said, the projected income from the non-oil/gas sector of Rp 80.1 trillion may be realized by increasing income from the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector of Rp 66.1 triliun, or 63.3% of all income from domestic sources, especially from income and value-added \b \highlight22