\par\par \b \uc2  Army chief warns against panic buying. \b0\par\par\uc2 907 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 January 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  2 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Army Chief of Staff Gen. Wiranto lamented yesterday unfounded rumors on the shortage of basic commodities which had triggered panic buying, and warned people against stockpiling daily needs for their own benefit. \par \par \uc2  Wiranto said the stockpiling buyers could be charged with committing crimes or even subversion for causing unrest. \par \par \uc2  "The Armed Forces will not hesitate to take actions against those who take advantage of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis," Wiranto said on the sidelines of a People's Consultative Assembly meeting yesterday. \par \par \uc2  He said the Armed Forces is undertaking all measures to combat rumors across the archipelago, including safeguarding the commodities to ensure that people can buy basic necessities. The military have also been deployed to calm the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 , according to Wiranto. \par \par \uc2  "I call on the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  not to trust the baseless rumors, which are intended to shake national stability and in the end to threaten the government's legitimacy," he said. \par \par \uc2  He said he suspected that certain groups were behind the rumors and that the security authorities are now searching for those groups. \par \par \uc2  Wiranto said people would not have resorted to panic buying at traditional markets and supermarkets had they believed that stocks of basic commodities were sufficient. \par \par \uc2  Businessman Bambang Trihatmodjo joined in the criticism against those involved in panic buying, saying that they were vulnerable to rumors. \par \par \uc2  "People should not react excessively to the crisis. The government has ensured that there will be no scarcity of daily needs," he said. \par \par \uc2  He called on the nation to join forces and help the government cope with the crisis. "We will be strong if we unite, as we did in the past," he said. \par \par \uc2  Chief of the United Development Party (PPP) faction in the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Hamzah Haz, said the panic buying was irrational, and urged the government to take concrete efforts to end the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  turmoil. \par \par \uc2  "All cabinet ministers, despite the fact they have only two months left to end their terms, must work hard and advise the President without waiting for him to ask for it," Hamzah said. \par \par \uc2  He said the rupiah free-fall against the U.S. dollar should not inspire the government to devalue the currency as it would only cause people to lose their confidence in the rupiah further. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  observer Bambang Warih predicted that mounting international pressure would hit Indonesia for unveiling a disappointingly modest state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . He said it triggered a new plunge of currencies in some countries. \par \par \uc2  "The state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  has raised (questions) as to the government's seriousness in coping with the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis," said the former legislator. \par \par \uc2  Panic \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about the adequacy of the supply of basic commodities continued to prevail in some parts of the country yesterday. Traditional markets and supermarkets in Yogyakarta saw an influx of shoppers. \par \par \uc2  Prices were higher than ever. \par \par \uc2  In the Kotagede market, the IR-type or C4-type rice sold for Rp 2,300 per kilogram, Rp 300 higher than the previous day. The higher quality types of rice such as Rojo Lele, Cianjur, and Delanggu doubled to Rp 3,500 per kilogram. \par \par \uc2  "We just raised the price to follow the market. Otherwise, I would no longer be able to trade," said Mbok Ikem, a rice seller at the market. \par \par \uc2  The same price increase occurred at other traditional markets such as Beringharjo, Kranggan, and Sentul, where buyers queued in front of stalls since dawn yesterday. \par \par \uc2  The price of other daily needs such as sugar, cooking oil, pepper, and eggs rose sharply yesterday. Sugar was sold at Rp 2,200 per kilo, compared to the previous price of Rp 1,600. Cooking oil doubled from Rp 2,100 to Rp 4,300 per liter. Eggs sold at Rp 3,600 per kilo, a 50 percent price hike. \par \par \uc2  In some smaller shops, owners even refused to sell their merchandise due to the unstable price. \par \par \uc2  A long line of edgy buyers were seen in many of the ancient city's supermarkets such as Alfa and Hero on Jl. Solo, Gelael on Jl. Sudirman, and Mirota Kampus on Jl. Cik Di Tiro. \par \par \uc2  However, at least six supermarkets such as Super Ekonomi Malioboro, Matahari Malioboro, Galeria, Progo, Pamor, and Cemara Tujuh remained closed yesterday due to the fluctuating price. \par \par \uc2  In Bandung, panic buying was also apparent with people seen withdrawing their money from automatic teller machines. \par \par \uc2  Most of them took to the crowded stores and markets yesterday, shopping for basic commodities. \par \par \uc2  Head of the West Java logistics agency Chaerudin urged people not to worry about the stocks of rice and other daily needs, claiming that the agency had a sufficient supply. \par \par \uc2  He said the agency supplied 100,000 tons to feed 30 million people in the province for the next three months, until the harvest in April. \par \par \uc2  "There will be an additional 67,500 tons of rice coming from outside West Java such as Central and East Java and South Sulawesi this month," he added. \par \par \uc2  In Medan, North Sumatra Military Chief Maj. Gen. Rizal Nurdin told residents to rest be assured that the supply of basic commodities was sufficient. \par \par \uc2  "The stock is more than enough," he told the media after a coordinating meeting with local legislators, Medan mayoralty administration, and the local logistics agency. \par \par \uc2  The same frenzy was seen in Ujungpandang, the capital of South Sulawesi, where basic necessities' price rose by up to 50 percent yesterday. (43/23/44/21/30/swa/aan/amd) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du1a0079r\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
