\par\par \b \uc2  BankWatch downgrades Indonesian rating. \b0\par\par\uc2 541 \uc2 words\par \uc2 14 January 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  11 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Bank credit rating agency Thomson BankWatch downgraded its sovereign risk rating for Indonesia from BB to B+ on the country's heightening political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Thomson BankWatch sovereign risk director Betty J. Starkey said in a statement Monday, "This downgrade is based not only on the country's deteriorating financial situation, but more importantly on the heightening political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 ." \par \par \uc2  She noted the weakening \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  confidence in the country's political leadership had surfaced over the past several days, with signs of panic buying and hoarding on the part of local consumers and mounting calls for President Soeharto to step down. \par \par \uc2  "Overall, these increasing political pressures have raised the specter of a leadership crisis at a time of a deepening financial and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis," Starkey said. \par \par \uc2  BankWatch said it was especially concerned with the impact of the drastic fall of the rupiah against the U.S. dollar over the past week. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah has lost about 70 percent of its value against the dollar since July. \par \par \uc2  "As a result, short-term debt pressures and the risk of increased corporate bankruptcies have been exacerbated," BankWatch said. \par \par \uc2  "Now there is concern over whether the US$40 billion emergency assistance package arranged by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) last October will be sufficient to cover the country's mounting financial obligations," it said. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia's outstanding foreign debt stood at $118 billion as of last September, of which $65 billion was owed by the private sector. \par \par \uc2  BankWatch also shared new doubts over the Indonesian government's willingness to comply with the terms and targets of the IMF assistance package. \par \par \uc2  It said the 1998/1999 draft state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , announced last week, disregarded the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  targets set by the IMF. \par \par \uc2  The agency shared others' criticism that projections used in drafting the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  were unrealistic, especially those concerned with the exchange rate, annual \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and inflation. \par \par \uc2  "With most private forecasts predicting \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recession and double digit inflation this year, the government's budgetary and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  goals could prove difficult to meet," it said. \par \par \uc2  Starkey continued: "Even in the event of IMF compliance, we remain concerned over the adequacy of the current IMF package, especially in light of the country's continued financial deterioration." \par \par \uc2  Of even greater concern, Starkey said, was the weakening confidence in the current political leadership, the emerging prospect of increased social unrest - triggered by mounting unemployment - and lingering \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  over how the future political transition would unfold. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, Standard & Poor's Corp said from Tokyo yesterday it may further cut its ratings for the sovereign debt of Indonesia, South Korea, Malaysia and Thailand in 1998. \par \par \uc2  "Further downward rating actions may occur in Indonesia, Korea, Malaysia and Thailand," S&P president Leo O'Neill was quoted by Reuters as saying. \par \par \uc2  The Asian turmoil may also have an impact on the credit standing of governments outside the region "if the crisis deepens and adversely affects economies elsewhere," the statement quoted O'Neill as saying in his annual "State of the Global Credit Markets" report. \par \par \uc2  O'Neill also said the credit outlook for most Asian financial institutions was negative, while the outlook for most North American and Western European financial institutions was stable. (rid) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du1e007e7\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  BI urged to apply fixed exchange rate system. \b0\par\par\uc2 424 \uc2 words\par \uc2 14 January 1998\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  Economists have urged the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  to abandon the prevailing floating exchange rate system and apply the fixed exchange rate system which is pegged to the US dollar as a move to stabilize the exchange rate. \par \par \uc2  Rizal Ramli, Econit Advisory Group director, based his argument on two reasons. \par \par \uc2  Firstly, the existence of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  costs in the floating exchange rate system is high. Secondly, the current system allows external factors to play a role in deciding the rupiah-dollar exchange. \par \par \uc2  Currency centers in Singapore, London and New York, he said, play a decisive role in determining the value of the rupiah against the dollar. Yet, the volume of rupiah trading in those places is small and thin, rendering it irrational for the value of the rupiah to be decided by foreign fund managers. \par \par \uc2  "If we use the fixed exchange rate system, it will be us who decide the value of the rupiah, and this gives a sense of certainty to businessmen," he said on the sidelines of a seminar on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in Jakarta yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Economist Didik J. Rachbini says that a system change could be a good idea, but added that a safety instrument is called for to prevent the system from proceeding without curbs and as a means to control the value of the rupiah against turmoil marked by excess. \par \par \uc2  So far, says Rizal, the government has been on the defensive as opposed to being on the offensive in the face of the monetary crisis, making it susceptible to beatings by its detractors. \par \par \uc2  Another offensive move would be to make national banks healthy, he said. \par \par \uc2  "The program in question could not be executed merely by merging banks, but by enforcing structural reforms, including structural consolidation, debt-equity conversions, capital injection and improving liquidity. \par \par \uc2  The second offensive step, he added, is to restructure private sector debts. Conservative estimates put the ratio of capital to the size of private sector debt in Indonesia at 1:8. This is a minimum estimate as it assumes a dollar-rupiah exchange rate at 6,000. If the rate is lower the ratio would become even higher, making almost all members of the private sector in deep financial trouble. \par \par \uc2  The government can also step in and take over problematic conglomerates by using cheap funds and then allow a new management or a group of professionals to improve its performance. "This is what is meant by leveraged buy-out (LBO) using very cheap funds." (09/ab). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010922du1e0002e\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
