\par\par \b \uc2  Government offensive 'needed to defuse crisis'. \b0\par\par\uc2 594 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 January 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  12 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Noted economist Rizal Ramli has criticized the government for being too defensive in handling the financial crisis. \par \par \uc2  Rizal, a director of the Econit consulting agency, said a more offensive strategy was needed. \par \par \uc2  He said Wednesday the government's approach had forced it to become defensive, such as by denying various rumors and calming down fears, and it lost the ability to take initiatives. \par \par \uc2  Rizal cited two factors which caused government officials to become defensive. \par \par \uc2  First, "intellectual bankruptcy". Due to this weakness, technocrats had intellectually failed to solve the financial crisis, which had hit the country since July, he said. Instead, they sought for an easy way out, including by asking for foreign assistance and selling state assets at bargain prices. \par \par \uc2  The second factor was a "leaving mentality". With such a mentality, he said, many outgoing members of the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  only saw the weakness of the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  without giving any concrete solution. \par \par \uc2  Rizal cited several strategies to deal with the country's deepening financial troubles. \par \par \uc2  The government, for example, had to be based in reality by clearly stating the problems publicly. The political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  elite must also be willing to sacrifice. \par \par \uc2  Rizal said the current cabinet must be reshuffled, even before the completion of its five-year term in March to wipe out the "leaving mentality". \par \par \uc2  "In the run up to March, many things can be done, as has been shown by South Korea, which could rebuild confidence in two months," he said. "If the government fails to come out with an offensive strategy in the next three months, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  problems could become sociopolitical problems with extensive implications." \par \par \uc2  He said priorities, therefore, must be given to monetary and foreign exchange stability. \par \par \uc2  According to Rizal, there were four components of the offensive strategy to salvage the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  First, monetary and foreign exchange stability. He said Indonesia must leave the floating exchange rate system and return to a fixed exchange rate by pegging the rupiah to the U.S. dollar. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  costs of a floating system, which had been implemented since August last year, was considered too large. \par \par \uc2  The system opened ways for external forces to contribute to setting the exchange rate for the rupiah. Financial centers in Singapore, London and New York had become places that dealt in the fate of the rupiah, despite the small transactional volume of the currency in international markets. \par \par \uc2  Second, synchronization of the monetary and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies. The willingness to sacrifice and concrete measures must be shown in the State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Third, improving the health of national banks. The 1988 banking deregulation had boosted the growth of the domestic banking industry, Rizal said, but failed to provide a prudent management system. \par \par \uc2  To revive domestic banking conditions, a merger \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is not sufficient. It must be based on a thorough financial restructuring of the domestic banking system, including the conversion of debt into equity and injection of fresh capital. \par \par \uc2  Fourth, the restructuring of the overseas debt of private companies. A conservative estimate showed that the equity-to-debt ratio of Indonesian conglomerates stood at one-to-eight assuming an exchange rate of Rp 6,000 to the dollar, he said. \par \par \uc2  If the rupiah weakened from that level, many private business groups would technically be bankrupt. \par \par \uc2  Under such a critical condition, Rizal said, the government should come up with a restructuring of the country's business landscape. This might include a leverage buyout of troubled businesses by the government. (08) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du1f00a8f\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
