\par\par \b \uc2  Businesspeople vow to back govt reforms. \b0\par\par\uc2 944 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 January 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  12 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Indonesian business leaders have pledged their support for any reform measures to be taken by the government to cope with the country's monetary crisis. \par \par \uc2  "There's no need to blame each other again, we have to be responsible and take part in the restructuring of our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," Sofyan Wanandi, chairman of the Gemala Group, said after a meeting between Indonesian business leaders and executives of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Tuesday night. \par \par \uc2  About 120 local tycoons and leading entrepreneurs met with \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Governor J. Soedradjad Djiwandono to show their support for the revival of the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The chairman of the Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry, Aburizal Bakrie, said the chamber wanted to show the government that the private sector would unite in efforts to restore confidence in the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Businesspeople said they would back any decision resulting from government talks with the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to reform the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "The business sector waits eagerly for the success of the government in its talks with the IMF," Aburizal said. \par \par \uc2  President Soeharto is scheduled to meet with IMF managing director Michel Camdessus today, in which Camdessus is expected to finalize further details of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms. \par \par \uc2  Camdessus' visit is one of a series of important visits from IMF and American government officials this week to persuade the Indonesian government to stick to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms agreed to in October in exchange for the IMF-arranged bailout program to cope with the country's ailing \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  IMF first deputy managing director Stanley Fischer arrived in Indonesia earlier this week, followed by U.S. Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia has become the focal point of concerns by the IMF, the United States, and other large countries, after the rupiah crashed last week to over Rp 10,000, an over 70 percent drop in value since July, on concerns that the government might backslide on its commitment to reform measures. \par \par \uc2  Sofyan said the private sector was waiting for the result of the meeting to see what kind of action plan it would take to support the reforms. \par \par \uc2  "We are going to use the momentum of the IMF visit to show the unity of the private sector in helping the government cope with the crisis," Sofyan said. \par \par \uc2  Aburizal said the government needed to clearly disclose what reform measures it would take after talks with Camdessus. \par \par \uc2  "We need the government to detail the measures to be taken," Aburizal said. \par \par \uc2  Soedradjad \par \par \uc2  Soedradjad said Tuesday he received the private sector's support with delight. \par \par \uc2  "The assessment and willingness of the business sector to support the government and to find a way out of this turmoil will help us not only survive but also improve ourselves," he said. \par \par \uc2  He said both the government and the business sector would work to restore confidence in the rupiah by encouraging exporters to exchange their dollar holdings for rupiah. \par \par \uc2  The government would provide new foreign exchange swap facilities for exporting companies to replace existing ones. \par \par \uc2  "We expect to complete it within one or two days, if technical matters are settled and if owners of the exporting companies approve the new facilities," Soedradjad said. \par \par \uc2  He said the government had worked with exporters on technical matters of the new facilities. \par \par \uc2  "But we have to be careful so we aren't accused of subsidizing exporters. We have to come up with a balanced system that is acceptable by international rules and at the same time attractive to the private sector," he said. \par \par \uc2  Soedradjad said exporters kept their dollar holdings because there was \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the rupiah. Companies had to have dollars to import some materials and repay their foreign loans. \par \par \uc2  He said existing swap facilities for exporters were not attractive enough so exporters still preferred to hold on to their dollars. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia's imports were about US$3.7 billion a month, he said. \par \par \uc2  Soedradjad estimated the value of transactions in the foreign exchange market totaled about $8 billion a day. \par \par \uc2  Because there was a slowdown in the flow of dollars, and exporters were still holding on to their dollars, the value of transactions was declining, he said. \par \par \uc2  Asked why the rupiah continued to sink despite the "love rupiah" campaign that was recently launched, Soedradjad said the campaign was a morale movement. \par \par \uc2  "In market reality, it may not have any significant impact, because even if the rupiah strengthens here, it may fall in the London and New York markets," he said. \par \par \uc2  "This movement is symbolic to show that we are in this together, but if we all do this together, there may be improvement," he said. \par \par \uc2  Business and government leaders and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  figures have been endorsing the "love rupiah" campaign by publicly exchanging a large amount of dollars for rupiah at local banks this week. \par \par \uc2  Soedradjad said there was no need to continuously question the drop of the rupiah. "It's like people who keep asking you what grade you are in at school every month, when they know that you are still in the same grade." \par \par \uc2  Sofyan contributed the rupiah's wild fluctuation to speculation on the ongoing negotiations between the IMF and the government. \par \par \uc2  "I believe once there is a clear outcome of the meeting, the rupiah will regain strength, especially after the market sees the commitment of the IMF and other large countries to help us," he said. \par \par \uc2  Tuesday night's meeting was attended by owner and founder of the Salim Group Lim Sioe Liong, property mogul Ciputra, father and son tycoons Mochtar and James T. Riadi of the Lippo Group, and Prayogo Pangestu of the Barito Group. (das) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du1f00a8m\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Camdessus meets Soeharto Govt set to announce total reform program. \b0\par\par\uc2 514 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 January 1998\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus said that an announcement will be made today on the results of the ongoing talks between the IMF and the government of Indonesia on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, officials taking part in a Monetary Council meeting last night indicated that the finance and real sectors may be totally reformed. \par \par \uc2  "I will make the announcement on Thursday after meeting with the President," said Camdessus upon his arrival at Soekarno-Hatta airport yesterday afternoon, after which he immediately headed for Hotel Borobudur Intercontinental where he is staying. \par \par \uc2  Prior to his departure to Indonesia, according to Reuters, Camdessus told reporters in Singapore that Indonesia needs to take concrete steps to put her financial sector in order. \par \par \uc2  In his brief statement at Jakarta's airport, Camdessus says that the rupiah's fall against the US dollar has exceeded reasonable levels. \par \par \uc2  National Planning Minister Ginandjar Kartasasmita told reporters after attending the Monetary Council meeting last night that "We will do just about anything for the good of the country and to improve the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and restore \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  confidence in the rupiah." \par \par \uc2  Other officials also said there will be 'better policies which will soon be announced', but provided no details. \par \par \uc2  The IMF is reported to insist on the government to bring about radical adjustments in several sectors to stabilize the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , including abolishing fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 3-5 years, and deregulate the distribution system. \par \par \uc2  With regards to IMF's standby loan, the body reportedly requested the government to sign a document spelling out Indonesia's intention to stabilize the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in accordance with IMF proposals. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, IMF is said to have admitted that its strategy to help Indonesia resolve the monetary crisis had backfired. In the case of the closure of the 16 private banks, IMF was convinced that the move would restore \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  confidence in the Indonesian banking system, according to a secret document obtained by The New York Times, Reuters reported. \par \par \uc2  The banks' closure, said the IMF document, however failed to meet its objective and instead created panic as a result of the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 's no-confidence vote on the banking system. \par \par \uc2  The report said that political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in Indonesia has become greater as a result of IMF's misjudgement, which triggered off the fall of the country's banking system in a way that had an effect on other countries in the Asian region. \par \par \uc2  The allegation that IMF is the architect of the bankruptcy of Asia's banking system gets support from Harvard economist Jeffrey Sachs, who accused the IMF of making Asian economies worse than before as it had caused the fall of the region's banking sector. \par \par \uc2  The conditions imposed by IMF on Thailand, Indonesia and South Korea in relation with the closure of problematic banks only widened the spectrum of the crisis, he said in Singapore. \par \par \uc2  "Credits and the banking system in Thailand, Indonesia and South Korea are in shambles as many banks cannot even open letters of credit," he said. (ram/psf/ab/her). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010922du1f0002g\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
