\par\par \b \uc2  Rupiah remains weak. \b0\par\par\uc2 782 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 January 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Indonesia is facing a great dilemma in implementing the reinforced and strengthened \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms agreed upon with the International Monetary Fund last Thursday. The crux is that a persistently volatile and weakening rupiah would make it next to impossible to implement the 50-point package of sweeping, painful reform measures. \par \par \uc2  The level of the rupiah's exchange rate seems a much lesser problem than its stability. Businesspeople say it would be much better and conducive for businesses and investments if the rupiah's value against the U.S. dollar stabilize at, say, between 6,500 and 7,500, instead of spiraling between 6,000 and 9,000. Such a fairly stable band would allow for reasonable cost and risk calculations. \par \par \uc2  However, all analysts are attesting, and market sentiment has been demonstrating, that the rupiah's rate will remain highly volatile if the urgent problem of the private sector's short-term debts, estimated by the IMF at US$20 billion, is not adequately addressed and if political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  is not removed. The short-term debt overhang would make the foreign exchange market persistently nervous and place it under strong pressures, while monetary authorities would remain in the dark about the day-to-day requirements of dollars for debt repayment and servicing. \par \par \uc2  The government made the right decision not to bail out private-sector debtors, and predictably the reform package does not directly address the debt problem. This does not, however, mean that the debt problem can simply be ignored or left for the debtors themselves to settle. As previously mentioned, the private-sector debts also stand in the way of a stable rupiah. \par \par \uc2  The special team, headed by former minister Radius Prawiro, assigned by the President to help private-sector debtors to negotiate for debt rescheduling or rollovers, should act immediately to quickly take stock of the problem. This means that debtors who are insolvent, structurally weak and mismanaged should be allowed to declare bankruptcy and be liquidated through an expedient legal process. This would rub salt into the wound, but it would be much better for strengthening \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fundamentals. Allowing these insolvent enterprises to continue operations would not only affect the whole business climate, but also would stifle the effects of the reform package. \par \par \uc2  The solvent companies which are facing only short-term liquidity problems due to the rupiah turbulence should be helped in dealing with foreign creditors. We are confident that foreign creditors are now in a better mood to negotiate after President Soeharto showed stronger commitment to the reinforced reforms as the medium-term outlook of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  seemed more promising. \par \par \uc2  The fact that the IMF did not demand a pledge to carry out the strengthened reform package from anyone other than the President - as it did in South Korea last month by demanding the commitment from presidential candidate Kim Dae-jung - clearly means that the 76-year Soeharto will surely be reelected in March for a seventh five-year term. President Soeharto's explanations after the signing of the letter of intent on the reforms also provided a clear, firm signal that he will be in full charge and responsible for the implementation of the three-year package. \par \par \uc2  Yet, the market still harbors widespread \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about the future direction of government arising from the President's age and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  health as both Soeharto and the dominant Golkar political organization strongly uphold the convention on the announcement of a vice presidential candidate. Moreover, the people have yet to see a concrete start of a widely demanded gradual process of political reform to create good governance, seen mainly as a prerequisite for smooth implementation of reforms. All this makes the reform package lack credibility. \par \par \uc2  Obviously, we cannot afford to wait until March for a fairly stable rupiah exchange rate. The more devastating would be the impact if the rupiah's volatility persisted until April when the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be jolted by a new wave of steep price increases as a result of a gradual reduction of fuel oil, food and electricity \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The people who have been suffering a lot might then lose confidence in the benefits and efficacy of the reforms. \par \par \uc2  We therefore feel compelled for the umpteenth time to make this point. Given the unusually grave crisis the nation is now in, and the fact that the political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  stands firmly in the way of the rupiah's return to a fairly stable range of exchange rate, Golkar, together with the Armed Forces, after consultations with the President, should not wait until the first week of March, as the convention requires, to announce its candidate for the next vice president. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du1k00aj6\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  STOCK BRIEFING. \b0\par\par\uc2 506 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 January 1998\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  Rupiah went down 1,125 points (11.7%) to Rp. 9,575 to the dollar \par \par \uc2  On January 19, 1998, the value of rupiah went down 1,125 points (11.7%) from Rp. 8,450 (Friday, January 16) to Rp. 9,575. Local and foreign brokers basically agreed that the continuing decline of the value of rupiah against U.S. dollar is due to the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  regarding the ability of Indonesian private companies to pay their due debts. The continuing decline of rupiah is considered temporary and does not mean the IMF's intervention has failed. Meanwhile, other Asean currencies, except Singapore dollar, went up against the dollar. Malaysian ringgit went up from RM 4.2050 to RM 4.1650, baht went up from 53.25 to 52.87 baht, and peso went up from 41.352 peso to 41.000 peso to the dollar. Singapore dollar was dragged down by the continuing decline of rupiah, going down from Sin$ 1.7400 to Sin$ 1.7465. (m2/06/09/ind/psf/amu/gps) \par \par \uc2  Foreign investors pushed JSX index up 6% \par \par \uc2  On Monday, January 19, foreign investors continued buying shares of Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  companies that have large capitalization, pushing JSX index to go up 6% (25.108 points) to 439.028. Yesterday, net buying by foreign investors was recorded at Rp. 92.964 billion. A broker said that the weakening of rupiah pushed foreign investors to buy shares on the stock exchange floor. \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform that will be conducted under the IMF's guidance, and the merger plan of three \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  banks and two other private banks also contributed to the buying mood. (rr) \par \par \uc2  Jakarta Stock Exchange warned 11 \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  companies \par \par \uc2  The Jakarta Stock Exchange (JSX) issued a warning letter No. S-042/BEJ.2.4/0198 dated January 15, 1998 to 11 \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  companies that have not issued their financial report for the third quarter of 1997 that ended on September 30, 1997. The \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  companies are: PT Anwar Sierad, PT Jakarta Kyoei Steel Works, PT Mas Murni Indonesia, PT Miwon Indon