\par\par \b \uc2  RI remains attractive to foreign investors - Sanyoto. \b0\par\par\uc2 459 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 February 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  8 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Foreign investors still see Indonesia as an attractive site for investment despite the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis, State Minister of Investment Sanyoto Sastrowardoyo said yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Sanyoto said as many as 54 foreign investment projects worth US$3 billion were approved last month alone. \par \par \uc2  His office is studying another 97 foreign investment projects for approval. \par \par \uc2  "The foreign projects (approved last month) are long-term projects and investors believe Indonesia will be able to cope with the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis in the not too distant future," he said after a meeting with President Soeharto at his residence on Jl. Cendana, Jakarta. \par \par \uc2  Sanyoto estimated that the number of foreign investment projects to be approved this month would be about the same as last month. \par \par \uc2  He added domestic investment approvals remained high last month totaling Rp 9.6 trillion ($800 million) in value with 49 projects. \par \par \uc2  Last year, foreign investment approvals rose 13 percent in value to $33.8 billion but declined 11.4 percent in terms of the number of projects to 790. \par \par \uc2  Last year's domestic investment approvals totaled Rp 119.9 trillion with 718 projects. \par \par \uc2  "These figures show that foreign investors still believe in Indonesia's prospects and think the current \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis is only temporary in nature," the minister said. \par \par \uc2  The monetary crisis, which hit Indonesia in early July, has slashed the value of the rupiah by over 75 percent, causing \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in almost all business activities. \par \par \uc2  Mining \par \par \uc2  Sanyoto, who is also chairman of the Investment Planning Board, said the President approved 80 mining contracts of work (COWs) last week, 72 to mine mineral deposits and eight to develop coal deposits. \par \par \uc2  The 72 mineral COWs and the eight coal COWs are respectively parts of the seventh generation mineral COWs and the third generation coal COWs that were approved by the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  last year after months of discussion. \par \par \uc2  Differing from investment in other sectors, the existing law requires that foreign investment in the mining sector be approved by the House before being approved by the President. \par \par \uc2  Applications for the seventh generation mineral COWs and the third generation coal COWs were filed in 1996. \par \par \uc2  The government initially received 164 applications for the seventh generation mineral COWs and 12 applications for the third generation coal COWs. \par \par \uc2  As the House reviewed the contracts, 31 companies withdrew their applications due to financial difficulty or failure to find enough resources in their proposed contract areas. \par \par \uc2  The House approved the remaining 145 applications. \par \par \uc2  An informed source at the Ministry of Mines and Energy said, however, the President later asked the ministry to reduce the number to 80 in line with the government retrenchment program to cope with the current \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. (jsk/prb) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du23007i5\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
