\par\par \b \uc2  Businesses urge WB to help ease debt problem. \b0\par\par\uc2 786 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 February 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  8 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Indonesian business leaders have urged the World Bank to take a more active role in helping the country's ailing private sector through its affiliated International Finance Corporation (IFC). \par \par \uc2  Teddy P. Rahmat, president of the diversified Astra International company, said here yesterday the World Bank, through its affiliated IFC, should do more to help ease the country's private-debt crisis. \par \par \uc2  "We expect the IFC to be more aggressive in entering into the private sector," he said following a meeting of more than 30 Indonesian business leaders with World Bank President James Wolfenhson yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Teddy explained that both the World Bank and the Indonesian government could not directly bail out the country's huge private sector overseas debts. "But the IFC can. We think they have to be more active," he said. \par \par \uc2  The business leaders said there was an indication the World Bank would help to push IFC to be more active. \par \par \uc2  "But we have to work hard on our homework," Teddy said. \par \par \uc2  He said the government's IMF-sponsored \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms were already on the right tract. "We only need to implement them consistently," he said. \par \par \uc2  IFC is an affiliate of the World Bank which helps private enterprises in developing nations by mobilizing domestic and foreign capital, including its own. \par \par \uc2  As of October 1997, its loan commitments to Indonesian companies totaled US$1.4 billion. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia's corporate short-term foreign debts are believed to total $66 billion, a major factor in the sharp fall of the rupiah which has lost over 75 percent of its value since July last year. Solving the debt problem is seen as a critical point to revive the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  from its current severe crisis. \par \par \uc2  Wolfensohn met with the Indonesian business leaders to get first-hand information about the current crisis. \par \par \uc2  The meeting, which was closed to the media, followed his morning gathering with Indonesian non-governmental organization leaders and influential \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  figures. \par \par \uc2  Later in the afternoon, he had lunch with key government officials, including Minister of Trade and Industry Tunky Ariwibowo, Minister of Finance Mar'ie Muhammad and Coordinating Minister for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Finance Saleh Afiff. \par \par \uc2  Wolfensohn, who arrived in Jakarta Tuesday, also visited several slum areas in the capital. He is expected to leave the capital today to visit the Philippines and South Korea. \par \par \uc2  He previously visited Thailand, Singapore and Malaysia before coming to Indonesia on his regional tour. \par \par \uc2  "We expect the World Bank to echo the positive measures we've taken," said Irianto Ongko, chairman of the Ongko Group, pointing out that the World Bank could assure Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms and political system. \par \par \uc2  "The private sector expects the World Bank to believe that the country can recover from its current \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis in one to two years," said James T. Riady, vice chairman of the diversified Lippo Group. \par \par \uc2  He expected the crisis to bottom out within the next 12 months. "But the financial sector usually recovers eight months before the real sector," he said. \par \par \uc2  He believed the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  may rebound as soon as the end of March with foreign investors starting to reenter the country. \par \par \uc2  "The only major problem right now is regarding political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," he said. \par \par \uc2  The country will hold an election for the president and vice president in March. \par \par \uc2  Although the World Bank in principle does not intervene in private-debt situations, the business leaders hoped the international institution would play a mediator role between local debtors and foreign creditors. \par \par \uc2  "We need assistance in negotiating with lenders," said Aburizal Bakrie, head of the Indonesian Chamber of Commerce. \par \par \uc2  He said the business leaders also urged for greater efforts to reduce the rupiah's volatility through the establishment of a "currency board". He did not elaborate further. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah's volatility has been the main focus in the current \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. \par \par \uc2  One of Wolfensohn's major questions in yesterday's meeting regarded the sharp drop of the rupiah last month, when other crisis-hit regional currencies like the baht seemed to have already stabilized. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah hit a historic low last month when it closed at Rp 17,000 against the U.S. dollar in the Singapore currency market due to fears of the private debt problem and political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The Indonesian currency gained ground yesterday to close at 8,700, gaining from the previous day's closing at 9,900. The currency was helped by reports that Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong had proposed to help Indonesia finance its imports. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia announced a freeze on servicing the country's corporate foreign corporate debt last month to allow debtors to negotiate new deals with their creditors. (08/das). \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du25007k9\par }\page {\par\fs20\b  \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia \highlight\uc2  is studying the currency board system. \b0\par\par\uc2 556 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 February 1998\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  is studying the currency board system (CBS) and the possibility of pegging the value of rupiah to US dollars. \par \par \uc2  Yesterday, after meeting with World Bank President James Wolfensen, Governor of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Soedradjad Djiwandono stated that \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  is still studying the possibility of implementing currency board system in Indonesia, and that nothing has been decided yet. \par \par \uc2  Previously, various parties suggested the government to peg the rupiah against US dollar at around Rp. 5,000 per US$ 1 in order to stabilize the value of rupiah at a level suited to the calculation of the revised State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  Plan 1998-1999. The move is predicted to give a hard blow to speculators. Tanri Abeng, member of the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Financial Stabilization Board, confirmed that the Indonesian government has indeed found a way to deal with speculators. \par \par \uc2  Banking analyst Rijanto said that if the government implemented a pegging system, \b \highlight22\uc2 bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  should be ready to conduct an all out intervention to keep the amount of foreign exchange reserve at a safe level in order to support the system. What will emerge out of it is a system of controlled free foreign exchange regime. \par \par \uc2  Another Bisnis source said that the government had invited Steve H. Hanke (an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  consultant from the U.S.) to present a strategy to stabilize the value of rupiah by, among other things, pegging the currency to the dollar. The source added that the implementation of CBS, and the pegging of rupiah to the dollar at around Rp. 5,000, might cause a heavy buying of US dollars, hence draining Indonesia's foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 . An opinion shared by economist Kwik Kian Gie. Therefore, the implementation of CBS requires a foreign exchange reserve that is at least as large as the amount of M0 (money base). \par \par \uc2  Foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  According to Kurt Schuler, a CBS expert from the U.S., the amount of rupiah that potentially could be used to buy up US dollars equals to the amount of M0 (money base). Meaning that not all of M2 (circulating money) can be used to buy up dollars since a lot of rupiah are still needed for domestic business transaction. Data from \b \highlight22\uc2 bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  shows that by October 1997, the amount of M1 came to Rp. 67.35 trillion, while M2 came to Rp. 340.74 trillion. \par \par \uc2  Kurst explained that in order to safeguard the implementation of CBS, Indonesia needs to boost up exports or other \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities that generate revenues in hard currencies. \par \par \uc2  According to Kurt, Indonesia is facing a similar condition experienced by Hong Kong in 1982. \par \par \uc2  At that time Hong Kong was hit by \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  regarding the transfer of political power to the PRC. The declining confidence of foreign investors pushed the value of HK$ down to HK$9.00. Since September 1983, Hong Kong has pegged its currency to the dollar at HK$7.80 per US$ 1. \par \par \uc2  An \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  analyst from the University of Indonesia, Faisal Basri, said that it is impossible to implement a peg system under the international business communities that expect the modification of exchange rates from time to time. Indonesia implemented a fixed exchange rate system in 1971 when Prof. Widjojo Nitisastro was the Minister of Finance. \par \par \uc2  (m2/09/sut/im/psf). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010922du250005f\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
