\par\par \b \uc2  Local stock prices likely to consolidate this week. \b0\par\par\uc2 679 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 February 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  11 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Stock prices on the Jakarta Stock Exchange (JSX) are expected to consolidate this week after making a 10 percent gain last week, securities analysts have said. \par \par \uc2  The analysts said foreign funds might still enter the market but profit taking by local investors would make most prices stagnant. \par \par \uc2  Head of research at Pentasena Securities Mohammad Syahrial said most investors had not decided whether to make any long term investment in the country's financial market. \par \par \uc2  "This is why many investors are taking profits within just a few days," he said. \par \par \uc2  But other analysts said the benchmark Composite Index would not fall below the psychological 500-point level this week even though the trading outlook was not so promising. \par \par \uc2  Syahrial said some investors would take profits if the main price index hovered between 530 and 550 points this week. \par \par \uc2  "If the index goes down to hover between 500 and 530 points, more investors will enter the market again," he said. \par \par \uc2  According to analysts, the strengthening of the rupiah was crucial to the stock trading outlook. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah closed stable at 9,400/9,600 against the U.S. dollar Friday following \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  intervention, up from its close of 10,300 last Monday. \par \par \uc2  Stock analysts said the announcement of the government's new data on private corporate debt, which last week helped revive trading activities, would make investors more confident about the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Chairman of the Corporate Foreign Debt Settlement Team, Radius Prawiro, announced Friday that private Indonesian companies accounted for only US$23.07 billion of the $73.96 billion in foreign debts owed by the private sector with the remainder owed by foreign firms and joint venture companies. \par \par \uc2  "The new data tells us that the private sector problem is not as serious as we thought," one analyst said. \par \par \uc2  Other analysts said that some foreign investors were actively trading in the market but foreign players were mostly still reluctant to make big orders due to \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the country's political situation. \par \par \uc2  "Most investors who entered the market over the past few weeks were short-term investors. They are still cautious about the country's long term prospects especially the political situation," Syahrial said. \par \par \uc2  Riot \par \par \uc2  An angry mob attacked shops owned by ethnic Chinese in the main shopping street of Bima town, West Nusa Tenggara on Saturday due to rising prices of basic goods. \par \par \uc2  Savage protests about the soaring prices of staple goods erupted in several towns on the main islands of Java and Sulawesi before and after the Idul Fitri holiday. \par \par \uc2  "Riots like this will effect most business activities in the coming weeks especially prior to the Presidential election in March," an analyst with a joint venture securities firm said. \par \par \uc2  Members of the People's Consultative Assembly will convene from March 1 to March 11 to elect a new president. \par \par \uc2  The JSX Composite Index ended 21.94 points higher to close at 535.42 last week from 485.93 the previous week. \par \par \uc2  The daily average turnover rose 132 percent to 789.62 million shares changing hands last week against 339.26 million shares the previous week. \par \par \uc2  The daily average value rose 48 percent to Rp 791.61 billion ($83.32 million) last week from Rp 532.22 billion the previous week. \par \par \uc2  Stock brokers said last week's turnover was higher than the previous week because there were only three trading days the previous week. \par \par \uc2  Most regional markets including Indonesia were closed on Jan. 28 and Jan. 29 to celebrate the Lunar New Year holiday and Idul Fitri holiday. \par \par \uc2  Blue chip stocks ended mixed last week with state-owned telecommunications firm Telkom falling Rp 75 to Rp 4,275 and Bank Internasional Indonesia Rp 50 to Rp 575. Bank Negara Indonesia and Bank Dagang Nasional Indonesia remained unchanged at Rp 600 and Rp 325 respectively. \par \par \uc2  Satellite operator Indosat rose Rp 600 to Rp 16,800, cigarette maker Sampoerna Rp 250 to Rp 5,625 and Gudang Garam Rp 2,150 to Rp 14,200. (aly). \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du29007o4\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
