\par\par \b \uc2  Currency peg disadvantageous for RI - Analysts. \b0\par\par\uc2 922 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 February 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  8 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The establishment of a currency board system (CBS), which would peg the rupiah to a foreign currency, would be disadvantageous for Indonesia, analysts have said. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  analysts claimed yesterday that setting up a CBS would not directly solve the alarming problems of food shortages, unemployment, troubled banks, corporate foreign debts and political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  They stressed that the country would do better by sticking to its reform commitments in dealing with the current \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. \par \par \uc2  They also foresaw many long-term dangers if such a system were enacted. \par \par \uc2  In the short term, the CBS could make domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  increase, threatening ailing domestic banks and cash-strapped local businesses, the analysts, most of whom requested anonymity, said. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah rallied yesterday, boosting other Southeast Asian currencies on reports that it could be pegged to the U.S. dollar. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah closed at 7,400 against the U.S. dollar, up sharply from its close of 9,600 Monday when President Soeharto indicated he was considering fixing the rupiah's rate to "kill" speculators. \par \par \uc2  Supporters for the CBS urged the government to peg the rupiah to the U.S. dollar at the 5,000 level, equivalent to the target set in the government 1998/1999 draft \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "To prevent a rush for dollars when the CBS is installed, \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  could be boosted," said an analyst at a foreign exchange bank in Jakarta. \par \par \uc2  Analysts pointed out that in the long term, a CBS could potentially erode the country's trade balance and current account. \par \par \uc2  "The peg system may cause a deterioration in Indonesian export competitiveness," said Raden Pardede, an economist with state-owned PT Danareksa Securities. \par \par \uc2  The CBS is probably being considered because some analysts believe it can contain inflation. \par \par \uc2  In tandem with a rigorous US$43 billion International Monetary Fund-sponsored bailout package, the government has projected zero \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth this year with higher unemployment and a 20 percent inflation rate - ingredients for potential social unrest. \par \par \uc2  Despite government assurances that it is committed to the wide-ranging reforms connected to the IMF package - including slashing monopolies and allowing foreigners to enter into almost all sectors of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  - the rupiah has remained sharply undervalued. \par \par \uc2  The currency has lost 75 percent of its value from its level of Rp 2,450 against the dollar last July. \par \par \uc2  Early this month, U.S. economist Steve Hanke, a persistent advocate of the CBS, spent an hour discussing the system's merits with President Soeharto and his key \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  adviser, Widjojo Nitisastro. \par \par \uc2  The President said Monday that he would find ways to fight currency speculators, prompting opinions that he was talking about the CBS. \par \par \uc2  "Soeharto seems to be entertaining this idea because a currency board would answer the solvency problems of many debt-ridden corporations," said an analyst. \par \par \uc2  He added that the idea seemed to be a short cut for the aging leader to bring back financial stability. \par \par \uc2  Analysts believe the rupiah crisis is partly due to the country's mounting corporate foreign debt problems. The government recently announced that overseas debts for local private companies amounted to $23 billion. \par \par \uc2  The analysts said the CBS might not be a solution to the debt crisis. "Even at the Rp 5,000 level, not all companies could service their foreign debts," said an analyst with a joint-venture securities firm. \par \par \uc2  He added that the setting up of a CBS might prompt debt-ridden companies to compete for the available foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 , a situation that could induce ordinary people to follow suit. \par \par \uc2  He explained that Indonesia's money supply totaled some Rp 75 trillion. To bring the exchange rate to the Rp 5,000 level, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  would have to put up $16 billion to cover the system. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  has stated that its foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  total about $18 billion. \par \par \uc2  The analyst said the remaining $2 billion would be too small to service the country's foreign obligations. \par \par \uc2  "The only way to prevent such a stampede is to extend the repayment freezing \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," he pointed out. \par \par \uc2  "The feasibility of the CBS will depend on whether the government could provide political certainty, that investing in Indonesia is safe," he said. "Otherwise people will continue to change their local assets into dollars," he added. \par \par \uc2  He said the CBS had several advantages, including providing certainty in the rupiah's conversion rate, creating confidence in the country's monetary system and instilling macroeconomic discipline that limits \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  deficits and inflation since the government would limit rupiah circulation to the amount of U.S. dollars it held. \par \par \uc2  Nevertheless, some analysts opined that giving up the exchange rate system would be too much of a gamble in the longer term. \par \par \uc2  "We are in favor of doing our homework by staying on the course of reforms by resolving debt and banking problems," said Danareksa's Raden. \par \par \uc2  Several Indonesian businessmen expressed support for an adoption of the CBS. They include Boyke Gozali, president of Bank Tiara; Soebronto Laras, president of Indomobil Corp.; and Rossano Barrack, vice president of the Bimantara Group. \par \par \uc2  But Benny Santoso, finance director of the Salim Group, Indonesia's largest conglomerate, said it would be wise to first study the system's advantages and disadvantages before making a decision. \par \par \uc2  A senior economist at Gadjah Mada University, Sudijono Reksoprajitno, proposed an alternative, which he called the steady growth exchange rate system. This would allow for a limited daily appreciation of the exchange rate by 0.06 percent, for instance. (08/23/aly). \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du2b007pw\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
