\par\par \b \uc2  Expatriates set sail as  \highlight22\uc2 economy \highlight\uc2  sinks. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,255 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 February 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Indonesia may be no comparison to the immigrants' dreamland of United States, but it had a high growth in foreign workers during the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  boom. Now that the wheels are reversing and the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is ailing, expatriates are losing their jobs or being forced to adapt. The Jakarta Post's team - Budiman Moerdijat, Devi M. Asmarani, Edith Hartanto, Ridwan M. Sijabat, Stevie Emilia and Oka Budhi Yogaswara - covers the issue. \par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): On a quiet afternoon in one of the city's many malls, Plaza Senayan, two Korean housewives stroll about solemnly. They enter a designer clothing store, one that has for weeks been empty of customers, and begin what they call a "homecoming shopping". \par \par \uc2  "I will miss shopping in Indonesia among other things," says one of the women, both of whom request anonymity. \par \par \uc2  Within a week they will be heading back home to Seoul with their children, while their husbands, both engineers for a joint venture company, finish up the numbered days of their jobs here. \par \par \uc2  The families are being forced to leave their luxury houses in Kemang, South Jakarta, their BMWs and their dollar-denominated prosperity which they enjoy in shopping sprees in plush shopping malls. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  turmoil, it seems, has gobbled a large piece of the pie that used to belong to expatriates. \par \par \uc2  While grand-scale \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  skimming has practically closed the door on employment opportunities for millions of Indonesians, it has also scraped the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of nonessential, large \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 . And in some cases that includes foreign workers. \par \par \uc2  The currency crisis has slashed the value of the rupiah against the dollar by over 70 percent, resulting in a crumbling \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Virtually all sectors have been hit. \par \par \uc2  Companies which enjoyed high prosperity before are now being haunted by foreign loans, burdened by rising costs and slowed down by lower revenue. \par \par \uc2  They have no choice but to let go of their foreign workers. \par \par \uc2  Like the husbands of the two Korean women, foreign engineers and consultants are among those badly hit by the meltdown, as the crisis has forced companies to shelve development and expansion projects, as well as halt ongoing ones. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  works minister Radinal Moochtar said recently that many private companies had fired their foreign consultants because they could no longer afford to pay their mostly dollar-denominated salaries. \par \par \uc2  Foreign consultants from Europe or the United States receive monthly salaries of between US$5,000 and $15,000. Those from Asia receive between $1,000 and $4,000 a month. \par \par \uc2  Last July, one dollar was equal to about Rp 2,500, but it has now surged by over 300 percent to about Rp 8,000. \par \par \uc2  Compare that to the salary of a local consultant, who earns an average of Rp 7 million a month. \par \par \uc2  Since the crisis deepened, the government has repeatedly urged companies to let go of their foreign workers as they are a major cost in foreign exchange. \par \par \uc2  Manpower minister Abdul Latief claims the country previously spent about $3 billion a year on expatriates' earnings. \par \par \uc2  In the current situation, that is almost like a self-inflicted wound on an infected sore. \par \par \uc2  Advertising and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  relations companies, another badly hit sector, have also been forced to fire their foreign employees. \par \par \uc2  One of the country's most prominent \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  relation companies, Nama Network Communications, has become inactive and some of its staff have joined its competitor Indo-Pacific \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  Relations. \par \par \uc2  Perwanal DMB&B advertising agency's general manager, Yusca Ismail, says many advertising companies are not renewing their expatriate workers' contracts. \par \par \uc2  But, perhaps the sector is not as badly affected as the country's financial sector. \par \par \uc2  Major companies such as DBS Securities, PT Lippo Securities, PT Sasson Securities Indonesia and PT Credit Lyonnais Capital Indonesia started laying off key personnel, who were mostly paid in dollars, as early as last November. \par \par \uc2  Hotels, which were known to employ many expatriates, have also limited the number of foreign staff to three to five people. \par \par \uc2  The Sheraton ITT Corporation in Indonesia streamlined their staff before the crisis. \par \par \uc2  "We're moving towards employing three expats per hotel, consisting of a general manager and one or two chefs," says Angus Maclachlan, the company's marketing director. \par \par \uc2  Maclachlan says Sheraton now employs 25 expats in its 12 hotels in the country. \par \par \uc2  The manpower ministry recorded 48,417 expatriates as of last December. Last month alone, 17,000 had been repatriated, and this month an estimated 15,000 others have left. \par \par \uc2  The data says less than 16,000 foreign professionals are employed in the country now. \par \par \uc2  But not all expatriates are paid in dollars. \par \par \uc2  Some advertising and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  relations executives receive rupiah salaries but get other earnings in dollars, while some foreigners earn only rupiah. \par \par \uc2  Erik Schmitz, a former copy editor at an English publication, packed up his belongings and led his Indonesian wife back to America after less than a year of married life. \par \par \uc2  "The value of my salary has been more than halved against the U.S. dollar, and there's no point for me to live here," Erik says. \par \par \uc2  "I have school loans to repay at home," he says. \par \par \uc2  International moving companies are raking in profits with the mass exodus. Reports say business was 50 percent more last month than the same period in 1997. This month is expected to be as busy, although normally February is a slow month. \par \par \uc2  Compromise \par \par \uc2  Some expatriates have compromised and agreed to accept salaries in rupiah instead of dollars. \par \par \uc2  "I think there are two kinds of expatriates: those who are paid in rupiah and have less money, and those who are paid in dollars and possibly face dismissal because their companies cannot afford to pay them anymore," says Angus Freiser, a technical advisor for Indo-Ad. \par \par \uc2  Many of those who still receive dollars have agreed to receive a salary at a pegged exchange rate which is lower than current the rate. \par \par \uc2  "I don't think they have any objections nor choice, and I think they realize this is short term," Yusca says. \par \par \uc2  "Within a short period of time, we will come out of this better and they'll receive the same package they previously enjoyed," he adds. \par \par \uc2  There remains optimism among some expatriates. \par \par \uc2  Some who have lost their jobs remain in the country to shop around for another job before actually packing it in. \par \par \uc2  The talk around town is that many foreign companies will invest in the country's industries, as the government pledged to the International Monetary Fund that it would open up the market and \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to international investors in exchange for a $43 billion bailout. \par \par \uc2  Many acquisitions will take place soon, and employing expatriates may become affordable again. \par \par \uc2  "There's a lot of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  at this point and companies may have to increase staff, and then reduce them for a while," says Scott Coffey, former director of Internet website provider Indo Exchange. \par \par \uc2  "But this is just a little hiccup and a temporary rough-up," he says. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia is a focus of Europe and the United States because of its strategic location. \par \par \uc2  Once foreign investment comes flowing into the country again, expats are going to return, he adds. \par \par \uc2  Coffey resigned from his job as president of his own company, Indo Exchange, a website operator which provides business, financial and capital market information. \par \par \uc2  He will soon join a U.S. company which is considering buying an Indonesian company. \par \par \uc2  "I want to take part in restructuring Indonesian companies, it is very exciting," he says. (team) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du2f007xz\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
