\par\par \b \uc2  RI needs pro-reform cabinet to improve  \highlight22\uc2 economy \highlight\uc2 . \b0\par\par\uc2 975 \uc2 words\par \uc2 16 February 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The rupiah remains weak and prices are skyrocketing, triggering riots in several towns. Economist Emil Salim, who held portfolios in three previous cabinets, discusses the necessity for Indonesia to have a credible pro-reform cabinet to improve the nation's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political condition. \par \par \uc2  Question: The government has introduced overall \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms but why does the rupiah remain weak and why do prices continue rising? \par \par \uc2  Emil: The rupiah remains weak because the implementation of the reform measures, which are actually very good, has not been smooth and consistent. \par \par \uc2  I see that some cabinet members in the last few weeks of their tenure have halfheartedly implemented the reform measures. Local administrations are also reluctant to abolish local fees as required by the reform measures. \par \par \uc2  The government lost some of its credibility when it backtracked on the previous reform package (November), for example, by reviving the projects previously shelved or postponed and then stopping again the same projects a few months later. \par \par \uc2  This indicates a strong battle between pro-reform officials and those wanting to maintain status quo. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, supplies of essential commodities become scarce and prices are skyrocketing because many traders and distributors, feeling \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  about the wild volatility of the rupiah, temporarily halted their trading activities to wait for prices to stabilize while some others speculatively raised prices to match the changes in the rupiah exchange rate. \par \par \uc2  Q: You don't see any sabotage efforts? \par \par \uc2  E: There are a few cases of sabotage but in general, traders are piling up goods because of the high degree of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Q: How do you see the recent rioting in several towns? \par \par \uc2  E: Social conditions are always vulnerable when there are massive labor layoffs, while prices are rising steeply. Some riots might have been ignited by certain parties for political goals but most of them have been spontaneous due to frustration with the difficult \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions. \par \par \uc2  Q: Do you see any attempt to divert the blame from the government to the ethnic Chinese? \par \par \uc2  E: I am not happy with that. Such a move, if any, is an irresponsible and futile move and that is cheap politics. Any party should not use racial, religious or ethnic sentiments as an agenda for political movements. \par \par \uc2  Q: Since the introduction of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform measures has not effectively restored confidence in the rupiah, do you think it necessary for the country to introduce political reform? \par \par \uc2  E: We do need political reform but we must be patient. We can start the political reform by seriously implementing the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform, which will eradicate the crony capitalism. \par \par \uc2  The 50-point \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform signed in January by President Soeharto and the managing director of the International Monetary Fund, Michel Camdessus, will abolish monopolies, restrictions on trade, nepotism in business and cartel-like organizations, which have produced the current political power. \par \par \uc2  So, implementation of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform would create a conducive climate for changing the pattern of political power and developing potential to create new political concepts. \par \par \uc2  From there, we will start the next step of political reform by, for example, introducing a new method of recruiting members of the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  through district-based general elections. The new House members will then introduce new laws to facilitate the democratization of the political system. \par \par \uc2  We cannot expect the introduction of pro-democracy laws from the current House members, who have been recruited under the old system. \par \par \uc2  Q: Why don't we start the political reform by establishing a cabinet whose members are committed to reform? \par \par \uc2  E: We can do so if we can appoint pro-reform people in the next cabinet, who will then initiate the introduction of political reform. But the slow implementation of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform indicates that the power of the antireform club is very strong. A few cabinet members are really in favor of reform but I wonder whether they have groomed their cadres. \par \par \uc2  Q: Now that all the factions in the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) are apparently determined to reelect the incumbent President Soeharto as the country's next president for his seventh term, do you think the next vice president can play a role in promoting political reform? \par \par \uc2  E: It depends on who will take that position. A vice president, who gets his position from the MPR, will have a power to do so. But I doubt the capability of the vice presidential candidates already put on the table. I think Pak Harto read the reactions of the people when the preferences were announced. \par \par \uc2  Q: You said recently that you would be ready if the MPR nominated you as a vice presidential candidate. What will you do if you are elected vice president? \par \par \uc2  E: I will push for the implementation of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform to eradicate crony capitalism. I will continue motivating ministers to carry out the reform and supervise closely its implementation until a clean and credible government is established. I will also see to it that the cabinet is clean from corruption and collusion. \par \par \uc2  Even if I am not elected vice president, I will continue my fight for firm implementation of the reform through my teachings, discussions, writing and non-governmental organization activities. \par \par \uc2  Q: Do you think that President Soeharto will be able to carry out Indonesia's leadership in the next five years? \par \par \uc2  E: We have no other alternatives. The facts show that the factions in the MPR find it difficult to look even for vice presidential candidates. \par \par \uc2  Q: Do you think the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will improve after the election of the next president and vice president in March? \par \par \uc2  E: It will depend on who will become the vice president and the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  team in the cabinet. The market will react positively if the cabinet comprises competent and credible personalities who are not corrupt. (riz) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du2g007zs\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  STOCK BRIEFING. \b0\par\par\uc2 623 \uc2 words\par \uc2 16 February 1998\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  Net selling by foreign investors came to Rp. 32 billion last week \par \par \uc2  Last week, net selling by foreign investors came to Rp. 32 billion following anxieties surrounding the heating up of political tension and the controversial plan to implement currency board system (CBS). The net selling brought JSX's capitalization to a figure below Rp. 200 trillion. While capitalization came down to Rp. 184.325, JSX index went down 86.96 points (16.4%) to 44.29. Analyst from Paribas Asian Equity said that foreign investors are currently focusing their attention on CBS, negotiations between Indonesian debtors and their foreign lenders, and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in China, Hong Kong, and South Korea. He added, as quoted by the AFX New York, the implementation of CBS will require a transition period in Indonesia, and during the period, \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  will go up. (06) \par \par \uc2  Foreign investors ready to take over properties in Indonesia \par \par \uc2  Technical advisor of PT Procon Ian David (who is also a Director of Jones Lang Wootton - JLW) said that foreign investors (big institutional investors, pension funds, multinational insurance companies, and investment funds), mostly from the U.S. and Europe, and the rest are from Hong Kong, Australia, and the Middle East, have allocated US$500 million to take over selected Indonesian properties, which prices have plummeted due to the monetary crisis. The take over targets are properties in and around Jakarta that are strategic and offer international quality. Previously, Procon stated that foreign investor had allocated US$ 300 million for the same purpose. Hence, the amount of fund to purchase Indonesian properties now have come to US$ 800 million. Most of the fund have been in the hands of Procon, which has been appointed to do the transaction in the take over o Indonesian properties. According to Procon, in the past three weeks foreign investors have been negotiating to buy 700 units of condominium worth US$ 42 million from five different projects in Jakarta. Recently there is a new order to buy 112 units of condominium worth US$ 50 million. (04/im) \par \par \uc2  Business people postpone raw material import \par \par \uc2  Although remaining stocks will only last until March 1998, importers keep postponing the import of raw materials. Chief of the National Association of Importers (GINSI) said that importers will resume their import activities in April when the exchange value has been stabilized by the government through the currency board system, hopefully at the rate of Rp. 5,000 per US$ 1. Currently there has been no new LCs opened since the value of rupiah is still fluctuating heavily. However, if the rupiah is not fixed at the above exchange rate, in April importers will start importing regardless the level of rupiah. Meanwhile, Chief of the Indonesian Association of Pharmaceutical Producers said that Indonesian pharmaceutical companies have not been opening new LCs lately due to the fluctuation of rupiah. (sup) \par \par \uc2  Approved domestic and foreign investments plunged down \par \par \uc2  Investment Coordination Bureau (BKPM) announced that the number of approved domestic and foreign investments in the month of January 1998 plunged down by 63.7% and 64.7% respectively compared to the same period last year. The number of approved foreign investments in January 1998 came to 29 projects worth US$ 2.6 billion, declining from last year's 80 projects worth US$ 3.55 billion. Out of the 29 projects, 14 projects are export-oriented in character. They are expected to export in the amount of US$ 298.9 million per annum, and employ 14,919 Indonesian people. Approved domestic investments also experienced a decline from 48 projects worth Rp. 21 trillion to 44 projets worth Rp. 7.4 trillion. The 44 projects are expected to employ 29,771 Indonesian people and. \par \par \uc2  (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010922du2g0007i\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
