\par\par \b \uc2  Banking stability needed to support currency peg. \b0\par\par\uc2 875 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 February 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The government seems determined to adopt a currency board system (CBS), under which the rupiah will be set at a fixed exchange rate to the U.S. dollar, to stabilize Indonesia's currency exchange rates. Manggi Habir, research director of PT Bahana Securities, discusses the issue. \par \par \uc2  Question: Do you consider that Indonesia is ready to adopt a currency board system (CBS)? \par \par \uc2  Habir: Indonesia's foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  will have to be sufficient to match all the rupiah in circulation. I think our present \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  of about US$17 billion are insufficient for this task. \par \par \uc2  Another big concern is that if a CBS is introduced at a time when \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  is high or confidence is low, a lot of people will choose to convert currency into dollars when the exchange rate is set at, let's say, Rp 5,000 or Rp 5,500. If that happens, you will have a contraction of the foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 , making it necessary to contract the money supply - the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  will have to raise \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  on \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Certificates to absorb the rupiah, which will cause commercial banking \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  to go up. If that happens, what you will have is very tight liquidity. \par \par \uc2  My greatest concern is for the banking sector, which is currently facing liquidity problems. Under a CBS, banks cannot go to the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  for liquidity (assistance). So, there is no lender of last resort. \par \par \uc2  Considering that situation, what advantages can we obtain and what risks will we expect if we implement a CBS at present? \par \par \uc2  If the CBS was implemented in a situation where we had enough foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  to cover the whole money supply and the banking system was strong, it would give us a stable exchange rate which would be a very positive thing for the business community. \par \par \uc2  But with all the concerns that I have mentioned, I don't think we are in the right condition to implement a CBS effectively. The risk is high because \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  could increase sharply and people could rush to buy dollars. \par \par \uc2  What impact would a turbulent U.S. dollar have on our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ? \par \par \uc2  If the dollar, to which the rupiah will be anchored under the planned CBS, fluctuates, our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be affected. \par \par \uc2  Do you think Indonesia needs supports from the International Monetary Fund (IMF), which is leading a $43 billion bailout package for the country? \par \par \uc2  The need for IMF involvement is more to do with restoring confidence in the market and ensuring that the Fund provides all the aid it has promised. Even though the IMF is no longer trying to attack the CBS directly, it is still worried about the conditions required to implement a CBS. If the confidence is not there, speculators on the international market might begin to attack the rupiah again once the CBS is in place. \par \par \uc2  Do you think a CBS would be contradictory to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms agreed with the IMF? \par \par \uc2  According to Steve Hanke, an American advising President Soeharto on currency board systems, it will be complementary to the IMF reform measures. \par \par \uc2  I think banking reforms recommended by the IMF first need to be undertaken before implementing the CBS. \par \par \uc2  Considering that the government appears quite confident about a CBS, how do you think money markets will react if such a system is introduced? \par \par \uc2  If it is introduced immediately, before the General Session of the People's Consultative Assembly (to elect the president and vice president for the next five-year term), markets will react unfavorably because there is no political certainty and negotiations between domestic debtors and their foreign creditors have not yet shown concrete progress. With progress on both of these fronts, markets will surely react better. \par \par \uc2  So, when is the most appropriate time for Indonesia to introduce a CBS? \par \par \uc2  I think the end of this year or early next year will the earliest appropriate time to introduce a CBS because by then debt problems in the private sector may have settled down, the banking sector should have been strengthened - minimum capital for commercial banks is being raised to Rp 1 trillion - and we will have seen how the next cabinet performs for more than six months. Furthermore, we expect that the country's current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which has arisen through increased exports and decreased imports, will have lessened by then, thereby helping increase our foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Commercial banks are still trying to increase their capital base through mergers and by inviting new foreign and domestic investors. Banks are also suffering from an increase in non-performing loans - about 5 percent to 15 percent of total loans. There is also a liquidity problem among banks. \par \par \uc2  At the end of this year, or early next year, we will know the market exchange rate and \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be falling. \par \par \uc2  But if the exchange rate settles down and \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  fall, do we still need a CBS? \par \par \uc2  No, but at least we will have options. Actually, I have a question: If the CBS is a such a good system by which to overcome an exchange rate problem, why are there only five countries throughout the world which have adopted it? (riz) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du2l008br\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
