\par\par \b \uc2  S&P's downgrades its ratings on 15 Indonesian banks. \b0\par\par\uc2 822 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 February 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  8 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): U.S. rating agency Standard & Poor's (S&P's) has downgraded its ratings of 15 Indonesian banks due to various \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 , including those associated with the country's plan to introduce a currency board system. \par \par \uc2  S&P's said yesterday the rating downgrades reflected its concerns over the incompleteness of the government's guarantee on bank obligations, continued market turmoil - including potential mergers - and new minimum paid-up capital requirements. \par \par \uc2  The long-term local currency ratings on Bank Internasional Indonesia (BII) and state Bank Negara Indonesia (BNI) remain on CreditWatch because of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  associated with the possible introduction of a currency board by the government. \par \par \uc2  A currency board system would peg the rupiah to a foreign currency, possibly the U.S. dollar, at a fixed exchange rate. \par \par \uc2  The rating agency said a government implementation of the system would run the risk of intensifying an already tight liquidity situation and further undermine the strength of the Indonesian banking sector. \par \par \uc2  The CreditWatch placements are likely to be resolved following a clear government decision on the currency board plan, the agency said. \par \par \uc2  The government's currency board plan has raised concern among analysts and major donors to Indonesia. The International Monetary Fund has threatened to cut off its US$43 billion rescue fund if the country proceeds with the plan. \par \par \uc2  Supporters of the system claim it is an appropriate mechanism to stabilize the rupiah and revive Indonesia's ailing \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which has been badly hit by the currency crisis. \par \par \uc2  S&P's specified that BNI's proposed takeover of state Bank Tabungan Negara was a CreditWatch issue. \par \par \uc2  The other banks downgraded by the agency are Bank Bali, Bank Bumi Daya, Bank Central Asia, Bank Dagang Nasional Indonesia, Bank Dagang Negara, Bank Ekspor Impor Indonesia, Bank Rakyat Indonesia, Bank Tabungan Negara, Lippo Bank and Panin Bank. \par \par \uc2  BNI, BII, Bank Danamon, Bank Niaga and Bank Umum Nasional were placed on CreditWatch, pending a resolution on the timeliness of the government's guarantee on bank obligations. \par \par \uc2  A CreditWatch highlights an emerging situation which may materially affect the profile of a rated corporation and can be designated as positive, developing or negative. \par \par \uc2  Following a full review, the rating may either be affirmed or changed in the direction indicated. \par \par \uc2  Guarantee \par \par \uc2  The government announced in January that it would guarantee foreign currency and rupiah-denominated claims by depositors and creditors (excluding loan capital and subordinated debt) of all locally incorporated banks (excluding banks closed by the government in November). \par \par \uc2  Under the guarantee, the government will pay foreign currency claims in rupiah at the market exchange rate quoted by \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The guarantee is effective for a two-year period, expiring Jan. 31, 2000, with a possible extension of a further six months. \par \par \uc2  Non-deposit obligations greater than an equivalent of $2 million must be registered with the Indonesian Banking Restructuring Agency (IBRA), a government body set up to rehabilitate banks. \par \par \uc2  While the mechanism for payments under the government guarantee imply that repayments will be timely, the guarantee does not cover all creditors, S&P's said. \par \par \uc2  The agency said the guidelines underlying the guarantee's implementation indicate that the government, through IBRA, has the right to set off a bank loan extended to a depositor or creditor against that party's deposit or debt obligations regardless of loan maturity, and to exclude certain creditors, such as related parties. \par \par \uc2  Technically, these rights, however well-intended, render the guarantee incomplete, undermining the support necessary to maintain the existing local currency ratings, S&P's explained. \par \par \uc2  While the guarantee is for an initial two-year period, S&P's ratings are beyond the range of the guarantee period, the agency said, adding that the local currency ratings take into consideration both the incompleteness of the government guarantee and longer-term profiles of each bank once the guarantee expires. \par \par \uc2  In the case of foreign currency claims, payments under the government guarantee will be in rupiah. S&P's said the repayment in a currency not originally contracted for would be regarded as a breach of financial obligation. \par \par \uc2  The agency said the foreign currency ratings on Indonesian banks reflected their innate capacity to repay obligations rather than their reliance on the government guarantee. \par \par \uc2  S&P's said downgrades were also affected by the government's recently announced requirement for each bank to have a minimum paid-up capital of Rp 1 trillion by the end of 1998, Rp 2 trillion by the end of 2000 and Rp 3 trillion by the end of 2003. \par \par \uc2  Only 10 banks currently satisfy the Rp 1 trillion requirement, the agency said, adding that the majority of the country's 212 banks are expected to have to merge to meet the new capital guidelines, changing the industry's dynamics. (08) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du2q008k8\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichg