\par\par \b \uc2  BOOK REVIEW - The dirty politics of the boardroom. \b0\par\par\uc2 726 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 March 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  6 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Politiking Di Panggung Bisnis (Politicization in the Business Sector) \par \par \uc2  By Rhenald Kasali \par \par \uc2  Published by Gramedia & TIARA, Jakarta, 1998 \par \par \uc2  241 pp + xxii \par \par \uc2  Rp 17,000 \par \par \uc2  YOGYAKARTA (JP): The meaning of politics has always been misunderstood as the effort to reach, capture and preserve power. People will justify any means to gain power, and politics has descended into a sort of barbarian arena where tricks and violence prevail. \par \par \uc2  Social unrest and political riots that occurred in every part of the country immediately before the 1997 general election, removed from the squabble of the elites in Jakarta, were the latest instances. \par \par \uc2  It turns out that political tricks are not only played out on their own stage, but also in business. This book reviews cases of politicization in that sector, where it proves to be as cruel, Machiavellian and ruthless as that in politics. \par \par \uc2  Most tellingly, Rhenald Kasali argues that destructive politicization behavior grows excessive when a country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  fails. \par \par \uc2  According to this management expert at the School of Economics of the University of Indonesia, the recession has dragged business into a vertical slide. A clear picture of how this occurs was shown by the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  failure in the U.S. between 1988-1993. In those years, the U.S. trade balance sank to the bottom in the aftermath of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  progress in Asia. \par \par \uc2  Consequently, several CEOs were removed from companies such as IBM, Apple, Amex, General Motors, Xerox, Procter and Gamble and Coca-Cola as they were considered unsuccessful in curing their firms' business ills. Even Lee Iacocca, the man who saved Chrysler, the pride of U.S. car manufacturers, was among the victims. \par \par \uc2  The timing of this book's release, amid Indonesia's acute \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis and the politically high risks involved, is perfect. It graphs a conspicuously growing politicization in the country. Cases cited are the Bapindo banking scandal, revocation of printing licenses for media, capital flight, malfeasance involving social security funds, diverging bids of state electricity company PLN, cancellation of mega projects and the sinking \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  confidence in banking institutions after the liquidation of 16 banks last year. \par \par \uc2  Politicization may flourish following the signing of an agreement by President Soeharto to conform to stipulations of the International Monetary Fund. These included reining in businesses dominated by monopolies and cartels. A consequence of Indonesia's wish to be part of global capitalism is that it must show respect for clean and transparent business practices. \par \par \uc2  Politicization spreads to a great extent because major entrepreneurs are identical to the rente-capitalists who are indeed susceptible to political changes. These nepotistic capitalists do not owe their success to hard work or achievements. They are able to diversify their business due to protection, licensing and facilities from a political patron. This is obviously distorted because it creates an unfair investment atmosphere. In turn, in Kasali's view, it leaves Indonesia's internal business institutions so weak that they are unable to withstand political turmoils. \par \par \uc2  According to this doctoral candidate from the University of Illinois, politicization becomes endemic because the fundamental \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  fails while the political situation remains in turmoil. In the approach to the 1998 General Session, now in progress, the political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  elite did indeed seem to be restless. Succession causes power to be dispersed rather than centered, and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  emerges because of the fear of losing privileges. The elite rely on contrived maneuvers to influence decision-making concerning their existence. Collusion is inevitable. \par \par \uc2  As Aristotle said, man is a political animal, which explains why politicization continues to exist on a massive scale in all sectors of life. Politicization can be performed by anyone, anywhere, anytime and affect anybody. Today you may be powerful, but tomorrow you are powerless; today at the head, tomorrow at the back; today praised, tomorrow abused. Thomas Hobbes' dictum homo homini lupus manifests itself in that way, and this is the essence of Kasali's argument. \par \par \uc2  This work may be a good reference for those who appreciate and put their trust in hard work, rather than nepotistic collusion, and who want to get ahead in business without stumbling on this supposedly nonpolitical stage. \par \par \uc2  - J. Sumardianta \par \par \uc2  The writer is a researcher at the Institute of Study on Human Interests (ISHI) and teacher at Kolese de Britto High School, Yogyakarta. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du320082t\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
