\par\par \b \uc2  Advertising shows slight upturn in April amid crisis. \b0\par\par\uc2 479 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 May 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  8 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The battered advertising industry registered a slight growth in business last month but long-term prospects remain \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 , an executive of an industry grouping said yesterday. \par \par \uc2  The secretary-general of the Association of Indonesian Advertising Companies (PPPI), Gunadi Sugiharso, said several advertising companies picked up activities again after months of suffering from dormant business. \par \par \uc2  "In quantity, there has been a decent rise, but value-wise, it has not been very significant," Gunadi told media on the sidelines of the association's routine working meeting. \par \par \uc2  PPPI estimated that advertising \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  dropped by about 70 percent in the first three months of this year from the usual Rp 4 billion (US$500,000). \par \par \uc2  But the gradual strengthening of the rupiah against the U.S. dollar in April prompted companies to begin advertising again, he said. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah, which bottomed out at over 12,000 against the U.S. dollar early this year, strengthened to about 7,500 against the greenback in the first three weeks of April. But it declined to about 8,000 this week. \par \par \uc2  Gunadi also attributed the slight growth in April to discounts of between 50 percent and 60 percent offered by the media. \par \par \uc2  However, advertising companies are unable to foresee the prospects of the advertising industry, he said, as \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  regarding the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  persisted. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah had yet to stabilize fully, and the level of domestic and foreign confidence in the government continued to hamper further growth of advertising, he said. \par \par \uc2  "Until certainty returns, companies cannot begin with their future plans." \par \par \uc2  Gunadi said consumer demand was still present even though people's purchasing power had sharply declined with the slumping rupiah. \par \par \uc2  Advertising companies must determine their direction, he said, an action which would involve changing their mental paradigm by analyzing opportunities. \par \par \uc2  Some might have to cease their business temporarily, and others would probably chose to "float" around while trying to survive by cutting costs sharply and restructuring their companies for more efficiency, he said. \par \par \uc2  There would also be those who would use any opportunities they could during the crisis to retain a cash flow, he said. \par \par \uc2  The director of PT Coca-Cola Indonesia, Bambang Bhakti, said in the meeting that the demand for advertisements continued, but these were more practical and functional than centered on imagery. \par \par \uc2  "There is a light at the end of the tunnel," he said. \par \par \uc2  Advertisers had all resources they needed: financial, physical, human capital resources, as well as business infrastructures and committed customers. \par \par \uc2  But they should provide a cash environment by accepting mostly orders that are paid in cash to prevent a situation of having to cover unpaid accounts of their clients. \par \par \uc2  They also should concentrate on core and volume-driven business by moving from a few big customers to many small ones, he said. (das) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du51009zg\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Selling pressures depress manufacturing stocks. \b0\par\par\uc2 319 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 May 1998\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA: Trading of manufacturing stocks was weak throughout last month, marked by selling pressures on investors. Almost all stocks in the sector were corrected lower. \par \par \uc2  Sectoral index fell a sharp 17.15%, from 94.02 to 77.90. During the same period, the Jakarta composite time fell 15 percent, from 541.424 on March 30 to 460.135 on April 30. The price correction of manufacturing stocks followed a bearish mood in the Jakarta Stock Exchange. \par \par \uc2  The Jakarta bourse simply lost positive sentiments due to the soaring \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . In the meantime, investors went on profit-taking move to secure their money. On average, each manufacturing stock got slashed by 18.64%. \par \par \uc2  Brokers said investors also felt discouraged by financial performance by a number of manufacturing companies last year. \par \par \uc2  Out of six companies that have issued financial statement, three of them suffered losses and two saw a decline in net profits. Only one company booked profit rise. \par \par \uc2  PT Astra International, for example, recorded losses of Rp 278 billion due to the rupiah plunge against the US dollar. Indocement also had to deal with forex exchange losses. In fact, the country's largest cement producer suffered foreign exchange losses of Rp 1.575 trillion. Modern Photo registered total losses of Rp 25.852 billion. \par \par \uc2  Paper producer Tjiwi Kimia is the only company that booked a significant increase in profits, from Rp 145.09 billion in 1996 to Rp 348.42 billion last year. \par \par \uc2  Overall trading of manufacturing stocks was weak last month. Investors are still in the dark over measures to settle private foreign debt and the second tranche of the IMF financial assistance package. \par \par \uc2  Total manufacturing shares changing hands reached 414.672 worth Rp 690.856 billion. This month, trading of manufacturing stocks is expected to remain weak due to high \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the macro \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  * Sigma Research Institute, Inc. \par \par \uc2  (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010922du560014y\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Economists question efficacy of SBI. \b0\par\par\uc2 916 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 May 1998\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  yesterday raised the \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  of its certificates (SBIs) by 4-12 points, depending on the periods, while a number of economists have questioned the efficacy of the monetary instrument in preventing the drop of the rupiah. \par \par \uc2  BI governor Sjahril Sabirin has announced that SBI \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  have been raised to 58% from 50% for one month and from 12% to 33% for 12 months. \par \par \uc2  The increase was made, he said, on the basis of recent developments related mostly to 'non-technical factors which have effected efforts to stabilize the rupiah.' \par \par \uc2  Moreover, he added, the step was taken to encourage long-term funds to enter the banking system. \par \par \uc2  "The SBI rates are flexible in the sense that it could either be raised or lowered according to our needs," he told the press here yesterday. \par \par \uc2  On 21 April, BI raised SBI rates, a.o. overnight from 40% to 44% and one-month from 45% to 50%. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, economists have come to dismiss SBI as ineffective in raising the rupiah as what they call a process of 'de-coupling' has taken place between the monetary instrument and exchange rates. \par \par \uc2  Econit director Rizal Ramli said that the de-coupling occurred because the rupiah has come under the influence of non-financial factors. \par \par \uc2  "The efficacy of SBI to strengthen the rupiah has become lower," he said after speaking in a seminar on tourism prospects here yesterday. \par \par \uc2  University of Indonesia economist Sri Mulyani Indrawati on the same occasion also questioned the SBI's efficacy amidst a situation marked by \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  caused by political factors. \par \par \uc2  "Neither is it effective in drawing external funds into the banking system." \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , she said, appears unsure when the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be over and raises SBI rates for the sake of maintaining \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  confidence in banks. \par \par \uc2  Rizal cautioned the government against pursuing the SBI \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as raising interest continuously spells the death knell of the real sector. \par \par \uc2  "I have many times said that we must reform the real sector in an all-out manner so that exports would rise and would automatically stabilize the rupiah," he said. \par \par \uc2  His view is shared by former banker I Njoman Moena, who said that so long as there is a gap between statements and actions on the part of the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , raising SBI rates would have little effect on the rupiah. \par \par \uc2  He cited the government's statement that the IMF financial assistance would only be used as \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  - and not to intervene - as an example, saying "it only makes it more difficult for market players to calculate exchange rates." \par \par \uc2  However, BI director Miranda Swaray Goeltom remains convinced that "the SBI is still effective especially to prevent aberrations in exchange rate movements." \par \par \uc2  The BI government added that increasing SBI rates forms part of an effort to stem the further fall of the rupiah. \par \par \uc2  He blamed the recent rupiah drop to non-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  factors. Despite the IMF's financial aid of US$1 billion, he said, the rupiah remained under pressure because of the riots that have taken place in the past two weeks. \par \par \uc2  Two days ago the rupiah was at around 8.000 to the dollar. Yesterday, however, according to data Dow Jones, it approached the 10.000 mark before closing at 9.570, down 870 points compared to Wednesday's level. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah was sold at the 9.200-9.925 range per dollar with a relatively low volume of US$126,345 million. \par \par \uc2  The highest volume was seen at the spot market with a total transaction of US$103,315 million, followed by the today and tomorrow markets at respectively US$13,245 million and US$9,285 million. \par \par \uc2  BI is said to have injected Rp4,960 trillion into the money market yesterday. The volume of SBIs that are due amounted to Rp4,970 trillion, while the amount of funds to be settled at the daily auction of SBI is Rp10 billion. \par \par \uc2  Despite the weakening of the rupiah, the JSX index (IHSG) yesterday strengthened by 22,53 points (5,3%). \par \par \uc2  The index was elevated to 436,778 from 414,625 the day before, thanks to overseas dual-listed shares which capitalized on the dollar's higher value by way of the arbitrage system. \par \par \uc2  In general, trading was buoyant marked by a transaction volume of 458 million shares worth Rp526 billion. \par \par \uc2  In the wake of higher SBI rates, a number of banks yesterday raised deposit \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  from 40% to 62,5%. \par \par \uc2  The banks are BBD, BDN, Bank Exim, Bank Putera, Bank Duta and Bank Bali. \par \par \uc2  BBD raised its deposit rates to 60% and 55% for one-and two-month periods, while for three-to six-month periods the rates are 48% and 36%, and for 12-month the figure is 35% from 22%. \par \par \uc2  Bank Exim set its rates at 62,5% and 48,5% for one-and three-month periods, while for six-and 12-month periods the figures are each 40%. \par \par \uc2  BDN raised its rates from 60,5% and 46% for respectively one-and three-month periods. \par \par \uc2  Bank Putera's rates are 52,5% and 35,75% for one-and three-month periods, while for six-and 12-month periods the figures are respectively 24,25% and 22,25%. \par \par \uc2  Bank Duta set its rates for one-and three-month periods at 52,5% and 36%, while for six-and 2-month periods the rates are 25% and 22%. (04/m2/asm/psf/dj/ab/msw). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010922du580015f\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
